    {
      "id": "971d2f9a07f9c686e041f0bff8726298b3e33554",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-08-10 02:06:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nPersonally, I'd prefer to pass in max-bits to lu_site_init instead of stack-type like LU_SITE_CLIENT/SERVER, because I think in real world user doesn't have requirement to have thousands of mounts, but do have requirement to traverse directories with millions of files (i.e: nasf's patch for ORNL), so I would suggest to add a tunable for client side, i.e: cli_object_hbits or sth like this, and pass it to lu_site_init from cli_site_init, lu_site_init will take the value as max-hash-bits if it's non-zero, otherwise it just use default.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "7822046389657aefc9bb6148e7af9d02cace5a91",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-08-10 02:13:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nI cannot imagine what the benefit is from the patch.\n\nHonestly, current hash implementation maybe cannot support 200+ logic clients on single node. But it is normal, because no customer wants to mount 200+ logic clients on single node today (except for testing). If it is really necessary to mount so many logic clients on single node, it is not on small node, it should be on very fat node, like SGI-XXX, maybe with hundreds of CPU cores and dozens of TB RAM, at that time, memory pressure is not big problem.\n\nOn the other hand, your patch will hurt hash performance. Because you shrink bucket bits of hash table, less hash buckets mean longer hash list in each hash bucket, which increases the average hash searching time.\n\nFor example, when you traversing large directory with 10M items. If all items are cached on client, if bucket bits is 15, then average hash bucket depth is 2^21/2^15=64, but if bucket bits is shrink to 13, then such depth is 2^21/2^13=256. Because we cannot control items to be scattered evenly to all hash buckets in the hash table (depends on hash function), so the really hash bucket depth is larger, maybe thousand, that is terrible.\n\nAs I understand, the patch is useful for your IR test, but maybe not for the real world configuration. So it is better to consider the performance issues more.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "08719e3baa860923386547bf3936ed1a52a64a10",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-08-10 02:44:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nThat's enough. I would like to use this patch for IR test only.\n\nI'm killing myself :-)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
