    {
      "id": "aad102d1d6d655b73bb753e553a72b5dbbf1551f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-08-12 17:12:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nSorry, this patch is unfortunately broken.\n\nAs I mentioned in a previous comment, now that I better understand that the client is also using lu_site, I would be OK with just using the first version of the patch (lu_cache_percent tunable) since this is such a minor issue.  Being able to land this patch to master is still important, since there will be other times where we want to mount 1000 times on a client.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "0127e8bef8d570d9e37a41882718c7d72739416e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-08-12 17:58:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nHi Andreas, thanks for inspection. I'll restore it to the 1st version. I have a stack of patch on my local side. If I have to fix one patch in the middle, I have to take out some patches on the top, and then reapply them after fixing. They are recognized as new patches by gerrit since new hash # are generated.\n\nDo you know a trick to fix this problem?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "3090240ebbdcca4c7af5c3d663bcde8c4aaed34f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-08-12 19:07:04.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 7.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
    {
      "id": "6f016b0a13c17366412ad21e253ce6df1e4a19fe",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-08-12 19:17:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 7:\n\nBuild Started http://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/1717/ ",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
    {
      "id": "5e2209ad847794fe9c6ad621c28aad803ef3036a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-08-12 21:45:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 7: Looks good to me, approved\n\nAs for modifying patches in the middle of a dependency chain, I don't know if there is any good way to do that.\n\nFor patches that are not strictly dependent upon each other, I've create local branches (one per patch, though I reuse them) so that they can all be submitted, inspected, updated, and landed independently.\n\nIn the case of your IR patches, this is a bit more complex since they do have a dependency on each of the separate patches, even if those patches do not have any dependency on each other.  I don't know of a good way to handle that.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
